                <head>No. 550.<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Frelinghuysen</persName> to Mr.
                            <persName type="to">Wallace</persName>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1883-06-14">
                            <hi rend="italic">June</hi> 14, 1883</date>.</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 88.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: Your dispatch No. 220, of May 22 last, has been
                    received, and the announced decision of the council of state presents the matter
                    of the petroleum concession in a grave light. It is hoped that your proposed
                    direct intercession with the Sultan may result in such a course being adopted by
                    the Turkish Government as will conform to the letter and spirit of existing
                    international engagements. You will, of course, keep the Department advised of
                    all that transpires, and especially of the views of your Russian and Roumanian
                    colleagues upon the subject.</p>
                <p>I am, &amp;c.,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>FRED’K T. FRELINGrHUYSEN.</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
